      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: my-container
        image: nginx
        ports:
        - containerPort: 8080
4ï¸âƒ£ Internal Communication & Connections
ğŸ“Œ End-to-End Request Flow
User â†’ DNS

www.example.com is resolved to the Load Balancerâ€™s IP.

DNS â†’ Load Balancer

The request hits the Load Balancer, which forwards it to Ingress.

Load Balancer â†’ Ingress Controller

Ingress rules decide how to route traffic.

Ingress â†’ Service

The Service finds the correct Pod based on labels.

Service â†’ Pod

The Pod processes the request and sends a response.

Response Path: Pod â†’ Service â†’ Ingress â†’ Load Balancer â†’ User

The request flows back to the user following the same path.

5ï¸âƒ£ Budget-Friendly Setup for a Startup
Since budget is a concern, hereâ€™s how to reduce costs: âœ… Use a free-tier Kubernetes cluster (EKS Free Tier in AWS, GKE Free Tier in Google Cloud).
âœ… Use a single-node cluster with auto-scaling to avoid unnecessary instances.
âœ… Use Ingress instead of a LoadBalancer Service (saves on AWS ELB costs).
âœ… Use ClusterIP Service instead of LoadBalancer Service (avoids external traffic costs).
âœ… Enable horizontal pod autoscaling (HPA) to add/remove Pods only when needed.

6ï¸âƒ£ Summary
âœ” A request to www.example.com follows a structured path:

DNS â†’ Load Balancer â†’ Ingress Controller â†’ Kubernetes Service â†’ Pod
âœ” Internal communication is managed by Kubernetes networking (kube-proxy, iptables, Service routing).
âœ” Using Kubernetes efficiently can help startups save on cloud costs.

